data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async bridge for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The opt-in you used in .NET 10 (`CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported` warning suppression) no longer exists. All synchronous LINQ operators now throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

**Every call in your repository breaks:**

| Sync (throws in .NET 11) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

**Migrated version:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- The Cosmos SDK itself is async-only; EF Core was bridging this with `Task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` internally — that bridge is now gone.
- `Add()` remains synchronous (it only tracks locally, no I/O).
- You'll need to propagate `async/await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.).
- Remove the old `ConfigureWarnings(w => w.Ignore(CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported))` from your `DbContext` configuration — it will cause a build warning since the event ID no longer exists.
